# Carnatic Guru-Shishya Knowledge Graph — Roo Session Rules

## Project layout
```
carnatic/
  data/musicians.json   ← canonical source of truth (nodes + edges + recordings)
  render.py             ← regenerates graph.html from musicians.json
  crawl.py              ← Wikipedia scraper (uses disk cache in data/cache/)
  serve.py              ← zero-dep local server, opens http://localhost:8765/graph.html
  graph.html            ← derived artefact — NEVER hand-edit
```

## Session startup
1. Read `data/musicians.json` before doing anything. That is the current state.
2. Read the **Open questions** section below — it is the living memory of this project.
3. At the end of every session: update the Open questions section, then `git add -A && git commit && git push`.

## Core workflow
1. User drops a Wikipedia URL, YouTube link+title, or verbal correction
2. Agent patches `musicians.json` (load → modify → check duplicates → save)
3. Run `python3 render.py` — confirm node/edge counts change as expected
4. Run `python3 serve.py` to visualise (or remind user to refresh if already running)
5. **End of session**: update Open questions below, then prompt: "Ready to commit — run `git add -A && git commit -m '<message>' && git push`?"

## Patching rules
- **Never edit `graph.html` by hand**
- Patch via Python: load JSON, modify in memory, save — never string-patch the file
- Log every change: `[NODE+]`, `[EDGE+]`, `[EDGE-]`, `[EDGE~]`
- Check for duplicate `id` (nodes) and `(source, target)` pair (edges) before appending

## Adding a musician
1. Fetch Wikipedia page; extract infobox `teacher`/`students` + prose lineage patterns
2. Check all existing `label` fields for name variant collisions before creating a node
3. Significance filter: Sangeetha Kalanidhi recipient, or necessary topological link
4. Use `note` to qualify: `"first guru"`, `"principal guru"`, `"gurukula training, N years"`
5. **Do not infer edges from shared bani** — require explicit lineage statement

## Adding YouTube recordings
- Links **must be annotated** with the video title (URL alone is not enough)
- Parse title → identify artist(s) → match to existing node `label`
- Extract 11-char video ID; append `{url, label}` to node's `youtube` array
- A recording can belong to multiple nodes (duets etc.)
- Flag unmatched artists — do not silently drop or create unevaluated nodes

## Data model quick reference
**Node:** `id` (snake_case, never rename), `label`, `wikipedia`, `born`, `died`, `era`, `instrument`, `bani`, `youtube[]`
**Edge:** `source` (guru id), `target` (shishya id), `confidence` (0–1), `source_url`, `note`
**Era values:** `trinity` · `bridge` · `golden_age` · `disseminator` · `living_pillars` · `contemporary`
**Instrument values:** `vocal` · `veena` · `violin` · `flute` · `mridangam` · `bharatanatyam` (add new freely)
**Confidence:** 0.95–1.0 explicit · 0.85–0.94 cross-confirmed · 0.70–0.84 single source · <0.70 speculative (must have `note`)

## Server
```bash
python3 carnatic/serve.py        # http://localhost:8765/graph.html
python3 carnatic/serve.py 9000   # custom port
```
YouTube embeds require localhost — never open graph.html as a file:// URL.

